edge and institutions: Natural resource governance is grounded in sound and diverse forms of knowledge and respect for diverse natural resource values and practices. Relatively strong alignment Tailor to the local context using a variety of approaches: FLR uses a variety of approaches that are adapted to the local social, cultural, economic and ecological values, needs, and landscape history. It draws on latest science and best practice, and traditional and Indigenous knowledge, and applies that information in the context of local capacities and existing or new governance structures. Devolution: Decisions are taken at the lowest possible level appropriate to the social and ecological systems being governed, with particular attention to supporting the roles and authority of local communities in natural resource governance. Weak alignment Engage stakeholders: ... actively engages stakeholders at different scales ... * * This FLR principle addresses engagement at different scales but does not address empowered devolution per se. Source: Springer et al. (2021). Source: FLR Principles agreed upon by the GPFLR (see Besseau et al. (2018), Fig. 4, p. 18). 6 Table 1: Alignment between NRGF and FLR principles (continued) NRGF principles FLR principles Strategic vision, direction and learning: Natural resource governance is guided by an overall vision of desired environmental and social ends, and allows for adaptation in response to learning and changing conditions. Moderate alignment Manage adaptively for long-term resilience: FLR seeks to enhance the resilience of the landscape and its stakeholders over the medium- and long- term. Restoration approaches should enhance species and genetic diversity and be adjusted over time to reflect changes in climate and other environmental conditions, knowledge, capacities, stakeholder needs and societal values. As restoration progresses, information from monitoring activities, research and stakeholder guidance should be integrated into management plans. Coordination and coherence: Actors involved in or affecting natural resource governance coordinate around a coherent set of strategies and management practices. Moderate alignment Focus on landscapes: FLR takes place within and across entire landscapes, not individual sites, representing mosaics of interacting land uses and management practices under various tenure and governance systems. It is at this scale that ecological, social and economic priorities can be balanced. Sustainable and equitably shared resources: Actors responsible for natural resource governance have the resources they need to carry out sustainable management and governance activities, including from the equitable sharing of benefits generated from natural resources. Moderate alignment Restore multiple functions for multiple benefits: FLR interventions aim to restore multiple ecological, social and economic functions across a landscape and generate a range of ecosystem goods and services that benefit multiple stakeholder groups.* * Also implied - though not explicitly addressed - by FLR principle on stakeholder engagement Accountability: Actors responsible for or affecting natural resource governance are accountable for their actions and the environmental and social impacts they produce. No directly aligned FLR principle Fair and effective rule of law: Natural resource-related laws and their application are fair, effective and protect fundamental rights. No directly aligned FLR principle Source: Springer et al. (2021). Source: FLR Principles agreed upon by the GPFLR (see Besseau et al. (2018), Fig. 4, p. 18). 7 Table 1: Alignment between NRGF and FLR principles (continued) NRGF principles FLR principles Access to justice and conflict resolution: People are able to seek and obtain remedies for grievances and resolve conflicts regarding land and natural resources. Weak alignment Also implied - though not explicitly addressed - by FLR principle on stakeholder engagement Reflected in cross-cutting NRGF value of sustaining nature Addressed as NRGF value Maintain and enhance natural ecosystems within landscapes: FLR does not lead to the conversion or destruction of natural forests or other ecosystems. It enhances the conservation, recovery and sustainable management of forests and other ecosystems. Source: Springer et al. (2021). Source: FLR Principles agreed upon by the GPFLR (see Besseau et al. (2018), Fig. 4, p. 18).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9ad0ac6c-45d6-407f-97fb-12d9972d18bf": {"__data__": {"id_": "9ad0ac6c-45d6-407f-97fb-12d9972d18bf", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/enhancing-integration-governance-forest-landscape-restoration", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Enhancing the integration of governance in forest landscape restoration opportunities assessments", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/enhancing-integration-governance-forest-landscape-restoration", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "98f1fdba5072d9d1d2bb04d910e1fd9748d6e474e4e956d74a976f9f35e9b992"}, "2": {"node_id": "e78ad69a-cd7e-456c-b211-81c7c3574319", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/enhancing-integration-governance-forest-landscape-restoration", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "19cd9f506d41d47b440a51666e8